  <h1>Beneficiary Letter — United Kingdom</h1>
  <p><strong>Prepared for:</strong> [Borrower Name] | <strong>Date:</strong> [Date]</p>

  <h2>What is an EPM?</h2>
  <p>The Equity Preservation Mortgage (EPM) is a regulated mortgage where loan proceeds are invested. Investment returns pay mortgage interest and provide monthly income.</p>

  <h2>What Your Beneficiaries Inherit</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The Property:</strong> Your home (freehold/leasehold), registered at HM Land Registry, subject to the mortgage</li>
    <li><strong>Estate Value:</strong> Property value MINUS mortgage balance</li>
    <li><strong>NNEG Protection:</strong> Ensures beneficiaries cannot inherit debt exceeding property value</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Settlement Process</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>Lender notified of your passing</li>
    <li>Estate executor contacts Lender with death certificate and grant of probate/administration</li>
    <li>Mortgage balance calculated</li>
    <li>Options: (a) Sell property via solicitor, pay Lender, remainder to beneficiaries; OR (b) Refinance/assume</li>
    <li>If property value < mortgage debt, NNEG insurance covers shortfall. No deficit recovery from estate.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Important Notes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Inheritance Tax (IHT):</strong> Property and estate value above £325,000 threshold are subject to 40% IHT. Your will and trust planning should address this. Consider life insurance to cover potential IHT liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Stamp Duty Land Tax (SDLT):</strong> On death, SDLT is not payable on transfer to beneficiaries.</li>
    <li><strong>Probate & Solicitor Fees:</strong> Estate will incur solicitor fees for probate and property transfer (typically 1-2% of estate value).</li>
    <li><strong>Leasehold Properties:</strong> If leasehold, ensure lease term is adequate (preferably >80 years) for future resale.</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Estate executors should seek independent legal advice from a solicitor regarding probate, IHT planning, property transfer, and any mortgage assumptions.</strong></p>
</div>

